Components
1. Model

The Model manages the application's data and business logic.

In DarshanEase:

User details
Temple information
Darshan slot booking
Payment records
Queue status

Responsibilities:

Store data in the database.
Validate booking information.
Update booking and payment status.
2. View

The View is the user interface through which devotees interact with the system.

In DarshanEase:

Login/Register page
Temple selection page
Slot booking page
Payment page
Booking confirmation page
Admin dashboard

Technologies:

HTML
CSS
Bootstrap
JavaScript
React (optional)
3. Controller

The Controller acts as the bridge between the View and the Model.

Responsibilities:

Receives user requests.
Validates user input.
Calls business services.
Retrieves data from the Model.
Returns results to the View.

Examples in DarshanEase:

UserController
BookingController
PaymentController
TempleController
AdminController
Working Process
The devotee opens the DarshanEase website.
The View displays the booking form.
The user selects a temple and booking slot.
The Controller receives the request.
The Controller checks slot availability using the Model.
The Model reads/writes data in the Database.
The Controller sends the booking result back to the View.
The View displays the booking confirmation.
Advantages of MVC in DarshanEase
Separation of Concerns: UI, business logic, and data are separated.
Easy Maintenance: Changes in the interface do not affect the database logic.
Scalability: New modules (e.g., donation, accommodation booking) can be added easily.
Code Reusability: Components can be reused across different modules.
Better Testing: Controllers and Models can be tested independently.
